english:
  title: Royal Edict Conferring Rank and Honor upon Han San-gun Lee Seok
  author: Lee Cham
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The King speaks thus: The way of rulership must rely upon the counsel of the seasoned and wise. In human affection, none are closer than those of old acquaintance. This truth has endured since ancient times—how could it ever waver?

    You, my friend, possess a nature bright as crystal and learning vast as the ocean. You are the exemplar of scholars and the diviner's oracle of our realm. In former days, I stood beside you in equal rank, and through long years of shared study, sincerity bound our hearts together. Through mutual refinement, our affection deepened like winter ice. Thus did we pledge that whether fortune smiled or sorrow came, we would walk the same path, unmoved by circumstance.

    Yet calamity struck our nation, and separation tore us asunder. How many seasons have we been denied each other's company? Yet my longing for you remains ever keen. When I founded this dynasty, I wished to govern alongside you. Therefore I granted you rank and fief, elevating you among the court's elder statesmen—not merely from sentiment for our past friendship, but trusting in your virtue and wisdom to bring order to both high and low society, and to hear your noble counsel.

    On the first day of this month, you came requesting leave to journey to the Yeo River. I was consumed with affairs of state and could not receive you in person. We parted with the promise that you would soon return. How could I have foreseen that tidings of your passing would arrive so suddenly?

    Reflecting upon that last meeting, my heart aches anew. Heaven has withdrawn its favor from me—it no longer aids my counsel. The sorrow that has befallen our weakened realm—who can measure it? Yet your noble spirit, if it yet abides, surely comprehends all that has transpired. This day I send an imperial servant to offer libations at your bier. Alas! Though the span of life, long or short, is ordained by Heaven and beyond our doubt, the rites of mourning and honor must be observed in full accord with the laws and customs of our realm.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Yeo River (驪江): A reference to a location, likely the author''s destination when summoned by the king.'
  - key: ''
    value: This appears to be a royal edict written upon the occasion of Lee Seok's death, delivered by King Yi Seong-gye (founder of the Joseon dynasty), eulogizing his long friendship with Lee Seok and recognizing his service to the state.
